{"title_page": "Petersberg (Siebengebirge)", "text_new": "{{unreferenced|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n|name= Petersberg\n|photo=Bonn Petersberg 2009 06 01 cropped.JPG\n|photo_caption=Petersberg mountain]\n|photo_size=\n|elevation_m=331\n|elevation_ref =\n|prominence_m =\n|prominence_ref=\n|location=[[North Rhine-Westphalia]], [[Germany]]\n|range=[[Siebengebirge]]\n|map = Germany North Rhine-Westphalia\n|coordinates = {{coord|50|41|10|N|7|12|27|E|type:mountain_region:DE-NW_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|coords_ref =\n|range_coordinates = \n|type=\n|age=\n|first_ascent=\n|easiest_route=\n}}\nThe '''Petersberg''' ({{convert|331|m}}), formerly known as the '''Stromberg''', is a [[mountain]]  in the [[Siebengebirge]] [[mountain range]] near [[Bonn]], [[Germany]]. It overlooks the cities of [[K\u00f6nigswinter]], on the right bank of the [[Rhine]] river, and Bonn on the opposite side. Today the peak is the site of the [[Hotel Petersberg]], which serves as a guest house of the [[Federal Republic of Germany]].\n\n== History ==\nThere is evidence that humans were already living on the Petersberg in 3500 BC. A ring wall constructed about 1000 BC has been excavated.\n\nIn 1189, by order of the [[Archbishop of Cologne]] [[Philipp von Heinsberg]], [[Cistercian]] monks from the abbey of Himmerod took over an abandoned hermitage built by [[Augustinians|Augustinian]]s. In 1202 the new [[Heisterbach Abbey]] was constructed in the Peterstal, the valley below the Petersberg.\n\nThe mountain was first known as ''Stromberg'' (as documented in 1142) and received its current name after a chapel dedicated to [[Saint Peter]] was erected on its peak in 1764. In 1834 the area was sold to the merchant Joseph Ludwig Mertens. His wife Sibylle Mertens-Schaafhausen built a summer residence on the Petersberg, and became known as the ''Rheingr\u00e4fin'' (\"countess of the Rhine\").\n\nAt the end of the 19th century the Nelles brothers from [[Cologne]] bought the area and by 1892 had opened the Hotel Petersberg, along with the ''[[Petersbergbahn]]'', a [[rack railway]] that linked it to K\u00f6nigswinter. In 1912 [[Ferdinand M\u00fclhens]] bought the property and the hotel was converted  into a spa. Terraces to overlook the Rhine and a new access road were built in the 1930s, whilst the railway closed in 1958. \n\nSince the [[second world war]], the hotel has served as the headquarters of the [[Allied High Commission]] for Germany, and as a guest house for the Federal German Government. Many world leaders have stayed there during official visits to Germany.\n<gallery mode=packed heights=165>\nFile:Kapelle Petersberg 2.jpg|Chapel dedicated to Saint Peter\nFile:Blick vom Petersberg auf das Rheintal.jpg|Dawn view from Petersberg into Rhine valley, showing the castle ruins on the [[Drachenfels (Siebengebirge)|Drachenfels]] and the [[Schloss Drachenburg]]\n</gallery>\n== External links ==\n*{{commonscat-inline|Petersberg (Siebengebirge)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Hills of the Siebengebirge]]\n[[Category:Mountains and hills of North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n[[Category:Petersberg (Siebengebirge)| ]]\n\n\n{{NorthRhineWestphalia-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{unreferenced|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n|name= Petersberg\n|photo=Bonn Petersberg 2009 06 01 cropped.JPG\n|photo_caption=Petersberg mountain]\n|photo_size=\n|elevation_m=331\n|elevation_ref =\n|prominence_m =\n|prominence_ref=\n|location=[[North Rhine-Westphalia]], [[Germany]]\n|range=[[Siebengebirge]]\n|map = Germany North Rhine-Westphalia\n|coordinates = {{coord|50|41|10|N|7|12|27|E|type:mountain_region:DE-NW_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|coords_ref =\n|range_coordinates = \n|type=\n|age=\n|first_ascent=\n|easiest_route=\n}}\nThe '''Petersberg''' ({{convert|331|m}}), formerly known as the '''Stromberg''', is a [[mountain]]  in the [[Siebengebirge]] [[mountain range]] near [[Bonn]], [[Germany]]. It overlooks the cities of [[K\u00f6nigswinter]], on the right bank of the [[Rhine]] river, and Bonn on the opposite side. Today the peak is the site of the [[Hotel Petersberg]], which serves as a guest house of the [[Federal Republic of Germany]].\n\n== History ==\nThere is evidence that humans were already living on the Petersberg in 3500 BC. A ring wall constructed about 1000 BC has been excavated.\n\nIn 1189, by order of the [[Archbishop of Cologne]] [[Philipp von Heinsberg]], [[Cistercian]] monks from the abbey of Himmerod took over an abandoned hermitage built by [[Augustinian]]s. In 1202 the new [[Heisterbach Abbey]] was constructed in the Peterstal, the valley below the Petersberg.\n\nThe mountain was first known as ''Stromberg'' (as documented in 1142) and received its current name after a chapel dedicated to [[Saint Peter]] was erected on its peak in 1764. In 1834 the area was sold to the merchant Joseph Ludwig Mertens. His wife Sibylle Mertens-Schaafhausen built a summer residence on the Petersberg, and became known as the ''Rheingr\u00e4fin'' (\"countess of the Rhine\").\n\nAt the end of the 19th century the Nelles brothers from [[Cologne]] bought the area and by 1892 had opened the Hotel Petersberg, along with the ''[[Petersbergbahn]]'', a [[rack railway]] that linked it to K\u00f6nigswinter. In 1912 [[Ferdinand M\u00fclhens]] bought the property and the hotel was converted  into a spa. Terraces to overlook the Rhine and a new access road were built in the 1930s, whilst the railway closed in 1958. \n\nSince the [[second world war]], the hotel has served as the headquarters of the [[Allied High Commission]] for Germany, and as a guest house for the Federal German Government. Many world leaders have stayed there during official visits to Germany.\n<gallery mode=packed heights=165>\nFile:Kapelle Petersberg 2.jpg|Chapel dedicated to Saint Peter\nFile:Blick vom Petersberg auf das Rheintal.jpg|Dawn view from Petersberg into Rhine valley, showing the castle ruins on the [[Drachenfels (Siebengebirge)|Drachenfels]] and